Author-Name: Gary Gorton
Author-Name: Guillermo Ordo?ez
Title: Collateral Crises
Abstract: Short-term collateralized debt, private money, is efficient if agents
are willing to lend without producing costly information about the
collateral backing the debt. When the economy relies on such informationally insensitive debt, firms with low quality collateral can borrow, generating a credit boom and an increase in output. Financial
fragility is endogenous; it builds up over time as information about
counterparties decays. A crisis occurs when a (possibly small) shock
causes agents to suddenly have incentives to produce information,
leading to a decline in output. A social planner would produce more
information than private agents but would not always want to eliminate
fragility.
